title: There's a trade off between visual acuity and sensitivity to light. Lions, at 13 cycles per degree, are just above the threshold for being legally blind in humans, which is 10 cycles per degree. But they can hunt at night. Eagles and other birds of prey are the only species with better acuity than humans, around twice ours measured by cycles per degree. None of them is nocturnal.
pid: f81eb477-bbdf-4fc2-8e30-ce0b4d417df5
